In this project, the training data for CBF is gathered and used for testing penalized versions of some linear regression approaches. The field of research in this project is representing the gathered data using 1D Fused Lasso and regression trees. The formula that is used for 1D Fused Lasso representation can be reached from the following link, in section 3.1. In 1D Fused Lasso representation, the aim is to find the best λ value that yields the least error. On the other hand, in regression tree representation, the objective is to find the best maximum depth setting. After finding the coefficients and obtaining the values of predictions for each representation method, comparisons will be made by calculating the mean squared errors and using 1-NN classifier method to choose the most accurate representation technique.

Task 1: 1D Fused Lasso Representation

1D Fused Lasso representation method is applied to the training data of CBF below.

#Empty lists are formed to keep the data generated in the for loop

fusedlasso <- list()
minlam <- list()

#For loop is constructed to apply 1D Fused Lasso representation method for k = 10

for (i in c(1:30)) {
  
    fused <- fusedlasso1d(as.matrix(cbftrain[id==i, 2:129]))
    fusedlasso[[i]] <- fused
    #Cross-validation is applied to keep the least λ value for each instance
    cv <- cv.trendfilter(fusedlasso[[i]], k = 10)
    minlam[[i]] <- cv$lambda.min
    
}

Task 2: Regression Tree Representation

Regression tree representation method is applied to the training data of CBF below after melting the data.

#The training data for CBF is melted and converted to long version for easier usage

long_cbftrain <- melt(cbftrain,id.vars=c('id','class'))
long_cbftrain[,time:=as.numeric(gsub("\\D", "", variable))-1]
long_cbftrain <- long_cbftrain[,list(id,class,time,value)]
long_cbftrain <- long_cbftrain[order(id,time)]
head(long_cbftrain)
##    id class time      value
## 1:  1     1    1 -0.4642765
## 2:  1     1    2 -0.5550479
## 3:  1     1    3 -0.8428431
## 4:  1     1    4 -0.8658955
## 5:  1     1    5 -0.9363963
## 6:  1     1    6 -0.8172700
#Empty lists are formed to keep the data generated in the for loop

treelist <- list()
maxdep <- list()

#Range values are decided to use in the investigation of maximum depth 

ranges <- list(minsplit=20, cp=0, minbucket=10, maxdepth=1:10)

#For loop is constructed to apply regression tree representation method

for (i in c(1:30)) {
    
    #Tune function is used to find optimal maximum depth values for each instances
    tuned <- tune(rpart, value~time, data=long_cbftrain[id==i], ranges=ranges)
    maxdep[[i]] <- tuned
    tree <- rpart(value~time, long_cbftrain[id==i], control=rpart.control(minsplit=20, minbucket=10, cp=0, maxdepth=maxdep[[i]]$best.parameters[,4]))
    treelist[[i]] <- tree
     
}

The resulting regression tree is plotted below.

selected_dt <- long_cbftrain[id==1]
tree_fit <- treelist[[1]]
fancyRpartPlot(tree_fit)

Task 3: Mean Squared Errors

In this task, actual values and the predictions made using two methods are collected in the same data table and mean squared errors are calculated.

#An empty list is formed to keep the data generated in the for loop

pred_values <- list()

#For loop is constructed to cluster the actual and predicted values

for (i in c(1:30)){
  
  series <- long_cbftrain[id==i]
  series[,tree_rep:=predict(treelist[[i]], series)]
  series[,fused_rep:=predict(fusedlasso[[i]], lambda=minlam[[i]], series)$fit]
  pred_values[[i]] <- series
  
}

Conclusion

When the performances of all three classifications are compared using the final accuracy values, it is seen that both representation techniques, regression tree method and fused lasso method, result in an improvement. If the performance of the two representation methods are compared, it can be concluded that fused lasso method provides a better prediction accuracy.
